I grew up playing this as a Flash game on PC gaming sites. It was free, no ads, had pretty much the same base content. Seeing it on mobile made me extremely nostalgic and happy to replay one of my favorite games. UNFORTUNATELY this game is plagued with an absurd amount of self promoting. I payed for this addition, being 2 dollars I expected it to be a no ad version. The free probably has tons of ads and revolves around micro transactions. BUT INSTEAD, this version is constantly plaguing me with ads to play every other edition of doodle something (devil, tanks, ect). The later game becomes completely impossible to discern what can be created. Snakes plus plane equals "censored"? I get the movie reference but without a time based micro transaction hint, it's almost impossible to know that fit into the same category as tavern or molotov. It looses all sense of creativity and originality for the sake of being a cash cow after already asking for 2 dollars at the door to rid other companies ads, yet no discern for backing you out of the crafting menu to force doodle devil in your face 60 times in the first hour of gameplay. I loved the game on pc, and recommend it over this mobile cash grab.

Doodle God is a fantastic little game.  While the premise is simple, combine 2 different elements to form 1 or more new elements, the game manages to never become boring. The main game (4 episodes plus artifacts) will keep most people busy for quite some time, provided they don't use hints or a walkthrough.  My only complaint would be the amount of content, as even after completing all of the bonus quests and puzzles, I still found myself wanting more (although this isn't necessarily a bad thing).  In short, I would definitely reccommend Doodle God to all gamers, both casual and hardcore alike, and even those who don't usually play mobile games (like myself).

I usually do not complain about in-app purchases when I am playing a free game. If the game is good enough, I'm happy enough to make a purchase or two to support the developer. I feel like I was conned into purchasing this game. After paying the purchase price, and using the initial amount of credits provided to you in the game, I was discovered to learn that all power-ups require this currency, and the only way to earn the currency is to fulfill advertisements, or pay additional cash.  The fact that these power ups only last 24 hours REAL TIME adds insult to injury. These types of games are usually played 15-30 minutes a day. Not a marathon session in 24 hours.  Really wish I could get a refund on this one. There are similar games to this created by far more reputable developers.  Gave them 1 additional star since the game looks good and runs smoothly.

While ads and their spam-level notifications can be disabled, their constant  reminder to buy in game points is obnoxious. In order to get hints you have to spend money. I paid for it, why can't I have any hints I want. Game itself is OK. Most irritating feature is that some combos aren't unlocked until after you have a certain number of elements created, so you have to constantly retry very combination you've done in the past. If you love creating spreadsheets to analyze all 256^2 combinations then this is the game for you. Otherwise find yourself a new game.
